  "local_port": 58786,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "I am repairing a soft steel chair by arc welding and keep burning holes in the metal, what can I do to make a strong joint?",
  "response": "When arc welding soft steel and encountering issues like burning holes, it's important to adjust your technique and settings to minimize heat input and control the welding process more effectively. Here are some steps you can take to achieve a strong joint without burning through the metal:\n\n1. **Adjust the Welding Current:**\n   - Reduce the amperage. Soft steel is thinner and more prone to burn-through, so using a lower current can help control the heat input and prevent overheating the metal.\n\n2. **Use the Correct Electrode Size:**\n   - Choose a smaller diameter electrode. Smaller electrodes require less current to operate, which helps in reducing the heat input to the workpiece.\n\n3. **Short Arc Length:**\n   - Maintain a shorter arc length. A shorter arc length helps in better control of the weld pool and reduces the heat affected zone, which can minimize the chances of burning through.\n\n4. **Travel Speed:**\n   - Increase your travel speed. Moving the electrode along the joint more quickly can help spread the heat and reduce the risk of burning holes in the metal. However, be careful not to go too fast, as this can lead to poor fusion.\n\n5. **Use a Backing:**\n   - If possible, use a backing bar or copper backing to help absorb and dissipate the heat. This can provide additional support and prevent burn-through.\n\n6. **Tack Welding:**\n   - Start with tack welds at intervals along the joint. This can help in aligning the pieces and provide a guide for the final weld. It also allows you to check your settings and technique before committing to the full weld.\n\n7. **Interpass Cooling:**\n   - Allow the metal to cool between weld passes if you are making multiple passes. This can help in managing the overall heat input and reduce distortion and burn-through.\n\n8. **Pulsing Technique:**\n   - If your welder supports it, use a pulse welding mode. This can help in controlling the heat input more precisely and can be particularly useful for thin materials.\n\n9. **Proper Joint Preparation:**\n   - Ensure the joint is properly prepared. A clean joint with the right bevel and fit-up can make a significant difference in the quality of the weld.\n\n10. **Practice and Experience:**\n    - Finally, practice makes perfect. If possible, practice on scrap pieces of similar thickness to get a feel for the right settings and techniques before working on your chair.\n\nBy implementing these strategies, you should be able to achieve a strong weld on your soft steel chair without burning holes in the metal.",
